# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-find-difficult-solve-problems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may find it difficult to solve problems or misunderstand questions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Model clearly how to identify key phrases and words which will identify the operation and equation required for word problems. This could involve drawing bar models or other representations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676486Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-unsure-why-dividend-divisor
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children are unsure as to why, when the dividend and divisor are equal, the quotient is equal to 1"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use physical resources  e.g. counters or children to represent both sharing and grouping contexts to help children to visualise the idea before applying to abstract equations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678461Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-find-product-total
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may confuse how to find the product (total amount)"@en ;
  curric:correction """Model use of terminology - ask children what various parts of the multiplication equation represents. E.g. 'The 2 represents how many coins there are.' ' The 5 represents the value of each coin.' 'That is the same as 5, 2 times."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678971Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confused-pound-sign-written
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may be confused by the pound sign being written before the digit rather than after. They may also include the pence sign as well as the pound sign when recording using the decimal point."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make deliberate errors for children to identify. Discuss the reason for correct notation. For example, explain that the pence sign is not needed in the decimal notation because we know the digits after the 'dot' (decimal point) indicate the pence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679004Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-groups-number-items
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may confuse groups with number of items in a group."@en ;
  curric:correction """Clear teacher modelling of groups, demarcating groups and physically placing items into groups e.g. a bundle of straws with an elastic band."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679009Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-difficulty-finding-one-less
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may have difficulty finding one less than a multiple of ten saying, for example, one less than 60 is 69."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Refer to the order of the decades counting forwards and backwards and encourage visualisation of the decades on number lines and one hundred squares to support this. Help children to generalise about the number before a decade number ending in 9"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-keywords-lesson-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often confuse the keywords of this lesson and use them interchangeably or incorrectly."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model correct usage in a range of contexts including labelling abstract equations and using the terms to identify the known elements in worded problems. Choral response can also support pupils using these words correctly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679066Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-multiple-ten-43
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think the multiple of ten before 43 is 30, or partition the subtrahend incorrectly when bridging, meaning they do not use the most efficient strategy."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Display and use the stem sentences to support articulation of how to find the previous multiple of ten. Use ten frames, number lines and one hundred squares to support with appropriate partitioning of numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679346Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-counting-steps-given-size
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When children are counting in steps of a given size, e.g. 2 p coins in twos, they may continue to count in twos when the coin changes."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to notice the value of the coins they are counting and to check their work using known addition facts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679391Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-solving-problems-particularly-new-contexts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When solving problems, particularly in new contexts, children may revert to inefficient strategies as they are focusing on the problem rather than the number involved."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to record the numbers involved on bar models, number lines or in equations, then focus on what they notice about the numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679442Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-able-explain-multiplication-expression
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children are not able to explain the multiplication expression."@en ;
  curric:correction """Children are encouraged to identify exactly how the equation relates to the image. For example 3 groups of 2 shoes: 3 x 2 - with the questions ‘What does the 3 represent?’ ‘What does the 2 represent?’ ‘What does the 6 represent?’"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679447Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-default-counting-ones-find
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may default to counting in ones to find ten more or ten less."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use representations that highlight the structure of the base 10 system, e.g. Base 10 blocks/one hundred squares, and also 'dual counting' to support understanding of 'unitising', i.e. that using 'ten' as a unit can help to calculate more efficiently."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679483Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-partition-second-addend-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may partition the second addend in a way that does not allow them to make use of the multiple of ten and use their number bonds to calculate efficiently."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use ten frames and number lines to support children in finding the multiple of ten and partition the addend in different ways to compare the efficiency of different ways of partitioning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679562Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-find-difficult-identify-factors
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may find it difficult to identify the factors in the word problems."@en ;
  curric:correction """Model how to address questions. Use of familiar stem sentences to support pupils in identifying the factors: 'There are 7 bamboos. Each bamboo is a length of 5 m. 7 is factor and 5 is factor.  We can skip count in ___ to find the product.'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679569Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-difficulty-understanding-different-ways
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may have difficulty understanding the different ways in which 'difference' can be represented and the language associated with this."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use a bar model to highlight the structure of the difference and create a range of problems, using different language, that could be solved using the same equation, e.g. problems which use both how many more and how many less/fewer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679627Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-difficulty-knowing-operation-required
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may have difficulty knowing which operation is required to solve a problem, particularly in those involving finding the difference."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to draw bar models or part-part-whole models to support their understanding of the structure of the problem and to articulate their thinking (as modelled in the lesson)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680008Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-subtracting-children-use-their-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When subtracting, children may use their number bonds to ten to find the correct ones digit, but may forget to consider the previous multiple of ten, e.g. say 40-2=48"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to use their knowledge of decades to estimate (e.g. I know 40-2 will be in the thirties), then prove it using representations that highlight the tens structure, e.g. one hundred squares, ten frames and number lines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-language-one-one-less-confuse
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The language of one more or one less than can confuse children, so 55 is one more than ? may be interpreted as 55 plus 1"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to articulate and explain in full sentences alongside number lines to support the understanding of the different ways to articulate the concept. Use stem sentences to support with this and display them around the classroom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680685Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-formed-generalisations-increase-decrease
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not have yet formed generalisations about the increase or decrease that takes place when numbers are added or subtracted, so may predict answers that are not logical or possible."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to generalise by posing errors to reason about, encouraging predictions about what will happen to the size of amounts when adding and subtracting. Encourage use of practical equipment to demonstrate their explanations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-recognise-known-facts-addends
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not recognise known facts when addends are presented in different order, e.g. they may not use 7+1 to solve 61 +7 They may also confuse tens and ones digits."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus on efficient ways of working and, when working in the abstract, partition the two-digit number into tens and ones, so the tens and ones digits can be easily identified and the commutative aspect of the ones digit can be more easily seen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680824Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understand-represent-repeated-addition
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not understand how to represent the repeated addition expression and a multiplication expression."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage pupils to identify exactly how the equation relates to the image: with the questions ‘What does the 3 represent?’ ‘What does the 2 represent?’ ‘What does the 6 represent?’"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-terminology-factor-product
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse the terminology of factor and product and therefore be inaccurate when describing equations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Take time to clearly model use of terminology and ask questions such as: 'What does the 3 represent?' 'What does the 5 represent?' 'What does the 15 represent?' Continue to explicitly use key terms such as factor and products within explanation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681349Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-group-size-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may confuse group size and number of groups."@en ;
  curric:correction """Clearly model the number of groups by demarcating groups where possible and using familiar stem sentences such as 'There are ___ groups.' Then, move onto identifying the amount of items / objects in each group. 'There are ___ in each group.'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681354Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-add-parts-instead-subtracting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may add the parts instead of subtracting a part to find the missing amount."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Give plenty of opportunities to act out stories and solve problems with practical objects. Encourage children to think about the size of the missing part in relation to the known parts, i.e. whether it will be larger or smaller than the other parts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681404Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-number-groups-value
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might confuse the number of groups with the value of the groups and therefore write incorrect expressions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Once familiar with building the relevant additive expression, the multiplicative expression is introduced alongside e.g. 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 is the same as 5 x 3  Take time to connect these ideas using `groups of language' and physical representations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681413Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-because-children-focusing-their-attention
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Because children are focusing their attention on the values of the coins, they may revert to inefficient strategies when adding coins."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model and draw attention to efficient strategies for addition as coins and notes are added, such as the use of doubles, multiplication facts or strategies for adding more than two numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681418Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-subtracting-children-partition-parts-tens
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When subtracting, children may partition both parts into tens and ones then subtract which leads to an incorrect answer when the tens are bridged."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explicitly discuss if the tens will be bridged before calculating and come to generalisation that, in subtracting, only one part is partitioned."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681457Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-comprehend-groups-zero
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may struggle to comprehend groups of zero. For example children may see four empty plates as four groups of one."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use a context where the number of groups is still visible when the group size is zero. Remember to make the distinction as to what is representing zero. Use the familiar stem sentences There are ___ groups of ___."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681842Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-automatically-link-know-additive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not automatically link what they know about additive relationships to money contexts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explicitly link known facts and stem sentences to money contexts where appropriate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-sphere-circular-face-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """May think that a sphere has a circular face because when drawn, a sphere looks like a circle."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Physically handle and compare spheres, cylinders and cones. Explore why a sphere cannot stand but a cylinder and a cone can."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687460Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-mix-direction-left-right
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some children may mix up the direction of left and right."@en ;
  curric:correction """Share different strategies for remembering left and right, such as wearing a wristband on your left, using your left hand to make an l-shape or relating left and right to which hand you write with."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687464Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-use-objects-measure-accurately
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not use objects to measure accurately, for example following the shape of the object they are measuring rather than placing objects in a straight line. They may miscount the objects."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to build a straight line of objects with no gaps first, then place the object they want to measure along the line. Encourage them to touch each object as they count."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687469Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-representing-two-digit-numbers-practically
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When representing two-digit numbers practically, children may start each number anew, instead of using what they know about number patterns to adapt existing representations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the questions 'What's the same?' and 'What's different?' to draw attention to the patterns in number sequences and how these can be used. Link the abstract to the pictorial and concrete by drawing attention to what each digit represents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687474Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-hard-draw-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may find it hard to draw their own number lines."@en ;
  curric:correction """Place the first, last and midpoint numbers first and use fingers or cubes to space the other numbers out equally."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687478Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-part-story-amount
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may find the ‘then’ part of the story, where the amount changes, difficult to identify."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Draw attention to the change, talking about it as a decrease."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687485Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-count-back-given
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may struggle to count on from, or back from, a given number."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage automaticity with the counting sequence through regular practice. At times, pause so that children need to predict the number that is one more/less. Initially, you may need to model silently counting from one through to the given number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687489Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-incorrectly-double-halve-find
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may incorrectly double or halve to find the missing products or factors."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The use of counters or visuals will help children to see the relationship between 10 and 5 in each context and support them to know when they must use doubling and when they must use halving."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687612Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-writing-equations-consecutive-numbers-children
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When writing equations with consecutive numbers, children may write in the order they are counted , e.g. 56-57 = forwards"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Give missing number equations and represent them on part-part-whole models and bar models to consolidate understanding of which numbers in the equation represent the whole and the parts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687757Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-muddle-order-numbers-bar
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may muddle the order of the numbers on a bar model and in a subtraction equation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """If children are not secure, then return to the concrete to secure understanding of this structure of subtraction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-patterns-identify-combinations-pupils
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When using patterns to identify combinations, pupils may struggle to be systematic and not identify all options systematically."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Spend time exploring the value of recording combinations within a simple table. Encourage checking, e.g. the amount of counters totals eight. Look for patterns and support children in spotting these."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-initially-struggle-first-second-contain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """May initially struggle with first and second as they do not contain the number names one and two."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Link these names to their shortened written forms (1st and 2nd) so children can see their relationship to one and two."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-reliance-counting-strategies-recognising-combinations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Reliance on counting strategies. Not recognising combinations of smaller quantities within 5"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Play games involving dice outside of the lesson to encourage subitising of more familiar arrangements. Then, look at those unfamiliar, such as the way a group of cubes appears when dropped onto a table. 'I can see ___ and ___. I can see ___!'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-incorrect-sequence-counting-recalling-next
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Incorrect sequence of counting when recalling the next and previous numbers."@en ;
  curric:correction """Start with parts of the sequence where pupils are confident to secure the concept of counting on for one more and back for one less."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-misrepresent-given-problem-meaning
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may misrepresent a given problem meaning they are led to calculate the solution incorrectly."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Children may identify the solution quickly when working with smaller numbers, but it is still important they are encouraged to visualise and represent each problem so that they know how to reveal the structure of the maths in more complex problems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understand-keyword-adjacent-difficulty
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not understand the keyword adjacent and have difficulty understanding the word problems."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model correct usage in a range of contexts including labelling abstract equations and using the term to identify the known elements in worded problems. Take time to show adjacent on number lines connecting to addition and subtraction of equal groups."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688031Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-rely-order-addends-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may rely on the order of the addends rather than their place value when calculating. They may also default to counting on rather than using known facts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Refer back to known facts and efficient strategies and model their use throughout, discussing the best strategy to use at each point and why. Model errors that can be made when not adding ones then tens for example, or in counting on in ones."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688070Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-make-connection-concrete
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may struggle to make the connection between the concrete, pictorial and abstract representations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When using the part–part–whole representation, make sure you explicitly connect each number with what it represents. Ask the children to describe what they can see using the full stem sentences. 'The ___ represents the __________.'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688076Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-recording-subtraction-show-difference-incorrectly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Recording a subtraction to show difference incorrectly e.g. knowing that the difference between 4 and 6 is 2, but recording this as 4 - 6 = 2"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stress we can compare 6 to 4 or 4 to 6, but remind children that subtraction is not commutative so the whole (/ the larger number of those being compared) has to be written first in the expression. We can however change the position of the = symbol."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688081Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-see-tens-ones
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that they must see both the tens and ones in a two-digit number to compare them. They may also reverse the tens and ones and compare the ones first."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure that numbers with the ones digit hidden are given to compare so that children can appreciate the relative size of the numbers. Use practical equipment and stem sentences to consolidate understanding of the structure of two-digit numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688086Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-metre-centimetre-similar
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that a metre and a centimetre are similar in length, due to the way they are presented in images that are not to scale."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Allow children to explore practically and develop a sense of the length of one centimetre and one metre. Find familiar items to reference specific lengths e.g. our classroom door is about one metre wide."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688090Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-see-link-adding-ones
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not see the link between adding ones and adding tens. They may add or subtract one instead of ten or muddle addition and subtraction, so may subtract ten instead of add ten to a number."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce understanding of unitising by describing each group of objects in ones or tens, e.g. five cubes plus 1 cube, 5 tens plus 1 ten and talk through what is happening. Show this with equipment in tens and ones such as straws or cubes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688196Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-connect-abstract-representations-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not connect more abstract representations of part-part-whole relationships with practical examples showing the five and a bit structure."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Take time to connect the representations pupils are familiar with e.g. show finger numeral representation alongside part-part-whole models and bar models to help pupils understand these all show the same relationship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-realise-count-missing-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not realise that a count with a missing number or number in the wrong place is incorrect."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce the stable order of counting to and from 10 and highlight clearly when the order is not correct or there is a number missing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688205Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-incorrectly-identify-parts-equation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may incorrectly identify parts of the equation."@en ;
  curric:correction """Multiple opportunities to label and call out the different parts of the equation will help children to become confident in using this new vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688392Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-multiples-5-10
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may assume that multiples of 5 and 10 are multiples of 10"@en ;
  curric:correction """Show children the relationship between 5s and 10s using the multiplication chart and number line. Make clear that even multiples of 5 are multiples of 10  Not all multiples of 10 are multiples of 5 Encourage discussions to highlight the relationship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688396Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-number-groups-amount
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse the number of groups with the amount altogether, for example, they may count 4 groups of 10 as 4 not 40  They may also confuse the number of groups with the group size."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Draw a ring around each group of 10 whilst using the stem sentence to help describe what you are seeing as you identify each group."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688401Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-grasp-why-5-5
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may not grasp why 5 + 5 is equal to 2 × 5"@en ;
  curric:correction """Continue to use the stem sentences to help children understand doubling; 5 + 5 is the same as 2 groups of 5. This is the same as 2 × 5. Children can use a 2 times table chart to help them answer questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-line-drawn-middle
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children may think that a line drawn through the middle of something means that the whole has been divided in half."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Children will benefit from practical experiences where they can explore finding half of shapes and objects in different ways. Encourage them to compare the size of the parts and make sure they are equal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688620Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-missing-numbers-count-able-start
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Missing out numbers in the count or not being able to start the count if not at 1."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Give a three number count in to establish a pattern before asking children to join in so 7, 8, 9 given before the children say 10."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688624Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-rely-counting-strategies-instead
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may rely on counting strategies instead of using known facts to subtract from larger numbers."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make comparisons between subtraction within 10 and within 20, looking for patterns. Make sure children notice that the ones digit stays the same when we subtract numbers with the same ones digits such as 5 - 2 and 15 - 2."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-see-double-two
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may struggle to see that a double is two of the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Spend time exploring doubles that can be found in the children's immediate environment e.g. using their hands or playing a game of dominoes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688726Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-presented-missing-number-equations-larger
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When presented with missing number equations with larger numbers, children may not automatically make the link to the part-part-whole structure."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use visual representations to consolidate understanding and to encourage children to manipulate the numbers or equations involved so they can utilise what they already know."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688730Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-get-tens-teens-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may get the tens and teens numbers confused and may muddle up the digits when writing the numerals."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show numbers on a place value chart and talk about what each number represents. Emphasise the relative value of the digits, focusing on the groups of 10 and how this is shown. Support pupils to generalise e.g. teen numbers always have one ten."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688735Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-realise-object-represent-whole
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not realise that an object can represent a whole as well as a part of a whole group."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore real life examples of wholes as individual objects as well as sets of objects, e.g. sweets, eggs, chocolates, pencils in boxes etc."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688990Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-getting-numbers-wrong-order-completing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Getting numbers in the wrong order when completing the stem sentences with one more and one less."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the representations to identify and support understanding of which value is one less and which is one more."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688994Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-secure-order-numbers-11-20
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Not being secure with the order of the numbers from 11 to 20 when not starting at 0 or 1."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Practice counting starting from different points within 11 to 20 and model the first 3 to establish a pattern."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688998Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-count-multiples-10s
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may struggle to count in multiples of 10s and recognise this as groups of 10"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use of concrete resources: 10 frame and 10 p coins can support children to practise skip counting in 10s. Then move onto counting in 10s on a number line."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689005Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-find-worded-problems-related
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may find worded problems related to adjacent multiples challenging if they are not clear on the structure of finding previous and next multiples."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model correct usage in a range of contexts including labelling abstract equations and using the term to identify the known elements in worded problems. Take time to show adjacent on number lines connecting to addition and subtraction of equal groups."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689152Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-describe-shapes-upside-its
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may describe shapes as 'upside down' or 'on its side' rather than describing the rotations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Display the keywords from previous lessons such as clockwise, quarter turn etc. Model describing the rotations using these keywords and provide opportunities for children to practice this when creating their own patterns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689156Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-make-mistakes-adopting-mental
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may make mistakes when adopting more mental strategies."@en ;
  curric:correction """Leave scaffolds in place until showing confidence in verbal explanation. For example, once confident visualising 'making 10' using the ten frame, remove the scaffold of the ten frame and counters."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689239Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-hard-understand-group
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may find it hard to understand that a group of objects can represent a whole."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the correct language to emphasise the 'whole group of ..........' and explore what happens when a part is missing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689243Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-see-bar-model-proportional
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not see the bar model as proportional, so may think that the parts are equal."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to see that the bars are proportional to help them get a sense of the size of the parts and whole."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-revert-inefficient-strategies-solve
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may revert to inefficient strategies to solve problems e.g. skip counting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Within the second learning cycle, children are encouraged to evaluate strategies used by others. The most efficient strategies should be discussed together throughout the first learning cycle to support with this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-forget-stop-their-count
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may forget to stop their count when giving an answer to a sharing problem."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the whole when writing equations and discussing problems. We count in 2s, 5s or 10s until we reach that whole. Stress that if we go further, we share more than we have to begin with."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689259Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-misunderstand-contexts-language-within
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may misunderstand the contexts or language within worded problems and therefore not understand the calculation required to solve."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model clearly how to identify key phrases and words which will identify the operation and equation required for word problems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689274Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-faced-problems-children-revert-using
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When faced with problems, children may revert to using inefficient counting strategies instead of more efficient calculation strategies."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Record equation required to solve a problem, then explicitly discuss the most efficient strategy to solve it, drawing on prior knowledge and strategies such as use of known facts and the bridge ten strategy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689439Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-solving-problems-involving-equations-two
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When solving problems involving equations with more than two parts, children may automatically consider the numbers in the order given instead of considering the order they would find easier."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to solve equations in different orders, comparing which they find easiest and articulating their thinking as they calculate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689443Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-understand-either-pair-addends
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not understand that either pair of addends can be added first and the sum will remain the same."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use concrete materials to represent the addends for children to explore, discussing what is the same (the addends) and what is different (the pair being added first)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689448Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-objects-10s-children-count-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When objects are in 10s, children may count the number of tens rather than the amount altogether."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Introduce errors involving confusion between the number of tens and the amount altogether for children to reason about."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689455Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-see-halving-inverse
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may struggle to see that halving is the inverse of doubling."@en ;
  curric:correction """Only progress to this lesson once children are fluent in doubling numbers zero to five. Present the same visual (e.g. 3 apples + 3 apples) and use this to discuss doubling and halving, revealing and covering one of the two equal parts each time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689619Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-without-correct-representation-children-struggle
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Without correct representation, children may struggle to know what to calculate."@en ;
  curric:correction """If needed, provide support at this stage so that the structure of the mathematics is clear to children."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689624Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-make-errors-halving-2
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may make errors when halving 2-digit numbers."@en ;
  curric:correction """Recap strategies for halving from previous units prior to the lesson so that the process of halving numbers does not take over the focus of this lesson."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689631Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lesson-deals-idea-minutes-past
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The lesson deals with the idea of minutes past the hour to 5 minutes past. Pupils may overgeneralise and say that when sixty minutes have gone past the hour we say sixty minutes past."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure plenty of time is spent dealing with this concept and that pupils are comfortable with the idea that when the minute hand is pointing to 12, it is an o'clock time with no minutes having gone past the hour."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689635Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-counting-used-solely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children think that 'counting on' is used solely as a strategy in addition."@en ;
  curric:correction """Children should be made aware that the strategy for 'counting on' can be used in addition but is used as a strategy for subtraction in this lesson where we are finding the difference between two numbers close in value."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689755Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-smaller-wholes-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that smaller wholes are only a part and that parts all have to look the same."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use a variety of real objects to demonstrate wholes and parts split and combined in different ways."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689759Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-know-later-zero-added-another
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Know later, when zero is added to another number, some children believe the answer is zero."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Secure the idea that zero shows that there is no amount in many ways. Give children zero [noun] to hold."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689764Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-link-sharing-problems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may struggle to link sharing problems with a division equation."@en ;
  curric:correction """Continue to stress that in sharing problems, the divisor represents the 'number of groups'. We are trying to find the 'size of each group'. It is important that pupils do not over generalise this to all division problems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-around-numbers-cross-tens
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Confusion around the numbers which cross the tens boundary, e.g. 39, 40 may say 39, 30"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make errors for the children to discuss; encourage them to  explain and correct mistakes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-identifying-number-groups
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may confuse identifying the number of groups and group size."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use sentence stems to support children's thinking and model writing the equation, e.g. for 2 groups of 5  we can say 2 × 5 For 5, two times we can say 5 × 2"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689780Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-larger-coins-greater
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that larger coins or a greater number of coins represents a larger value."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use pre-money tokens to draw attention to the value of the 5 p coin. When comparing 1 p and 5 p coins, ensure children swap coins for equivalent amounts to draw attention to the value of the coins as opposed to their size or quantity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-fully-understand-concept-unitising
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not fully understand the concept of unitising and may confuse the number of coins with the total value. They may also count sets of coins containing 5 p coins and other coins in fives."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use pre-money tokens with five spots alongside 5 p coins to start with to deepen the understanding of one coin representing a value of . Discuss deliberate errors, articulating thinking around why these cannot be correct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689791Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-partition-whole-parts-subtracting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may partition both the whole and the parts when subtracting two 2-digit numbers. They need to know to avoid this because it gives an incorrect answer when subtracting numbers which bridge 10"""@en ;
  curric:correction """You may wish to explore further examples which do and do not reach the correct answer, articulating why this is the case and coming to the generalisation that, when subtracting, only one part needs to be partitioned into tens and ones."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-finding-quarter-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse finding a quarter of a number with finding 4 of the objects, or finding a third of a number with finding 3 of the objects."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the stem sentence 'the whole has been divided into ___ equal parts' and draw a bar model to represent this before children attempt to find a quarter or a third of a number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-one-quarter-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may find one-quarter rather than three-quarters of an amount."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use gesture, colour and/or circling to highlight three-quarters of an amount. Use the stem sentences, 'one-quarter of the whole is ___, two-quarters of the whole is ___, three quarters of the whole is ___'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689911Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-consecutive-numbers-ordered
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may think that only consecutive numbers can be ordered."@en ;
  curric:correction """Order non-consecutive numbers, then place back with other numbers on number track to consolidate understanding of their relative size."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690122Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-recall-multiplication-facts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may struggle to recall multiplication facts related to the 5 and 10 times tables."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Using times table charts where needed throughout this unit will support children in recalling facts and enable them to focus on seeing the relationships, e.g. between the 5 and 10 times table. These can be used until children become more fluent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-record-numbers-partitioned-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children might record that numbers can only be partitioned in one way."@en ;
  curric:correction """Children here have the chance to explore how numbers can be partitioned in many different ways. Narrate when exploring these different ways throughout, using  ___ is the whole, ___ is a part and ___ is a part."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690135Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-unnecessarily-re-counting-objects-group
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Unnecessarily re-counting all objects in a group rather than counting on from an existing amount."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Repeat the key sentence, 'we start our count at ___, and we count ___'."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690238Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-recognise-1-factor-particularly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not recognise that 1 can be a factor, particularly when the context includes 1 group."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Work with children to discuss groups and what they can see, such as 3 groups of 4   Reduce the number of groups to 2 and then 1 group and identify that 1 group can still be used. Then attach this to multiplication and expressions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690242Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-resort-counting-strategies-without
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may resort to counting strategies without noticing that the relationship between the minuend and the subtrahend is that there is a difference of two."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Draw out the patterns that will allow children to solve these equations without needing to using counting strategies. For example, 5 + 2 and 2 + 5 are 'odd number after'; 7 - 2 is 'odd number before' and 7 - 5 is 'difference of two'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690395Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-write-fraction-notation-numerator
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may write fraction notation with the numerator and denominator the wrong way round."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the stem sentence shown in this lesson each time you write a fraction, and give children opportunities to explain what each numeral in the fraction represents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-square-rectangle
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may think that a square is not a rectangle."@en ;
  curric:correction """Count the sides and vertices of rectangles (including squares) to show they all have 4 (concept is revisited throughout Year 1 and beyond)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690406Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-understand-day-amount-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may understand a day as the amount of time in which they are awake."@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson counts and names each of the 24 hours, using morning, evening and night. Take time to discuss what the children will typically be doing during these hours, including when they will usually be asleep."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-adding-subtracting-zero
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that adding or subtracting zero gives zero. For example, 6 + 0 = 0 or 4 - 0 = 0"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use manipulatives to help children see that adding or subtracting zero will not change the starting amount. Model this alongside the written equation so that they can see what each part is representing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690714Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-difficulty-creating-problems-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children can have difficulty creating problems because they cannot process the amount of information needed and organise their thinking in the way necessary to know how to start."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Give criteria, such as the context, the numbers involved, an equation to represent, or a given structure of addition or subtraction to help focus and structure their thoughts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-fail-appreciate-importance-equals
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may fail to appreciate the importance of the equals sign in an equation, e.g. making errors such as 16 = 4 + 20, or confuse the value of the digits, making errors such as 43 = 4 + 30"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the language of parts and whole to activate/link to prior learning. Encourage drawing of own part-part-whole models. Encourage children to spot errors and explain why they are are incorrect and to articulate their thinking around correct answers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690723Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-rely-counting-ones-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may rely on counting in ones rather than recognise a group of ten."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to recognise groups of ten in a variety of contexts. They may need to check one e.g. a bundle of 10 straws but then should be encouraged to use comparative size to know other groups are of equal size."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690728Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-rely-counting-count-accurately
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may rely on counting all and may not count accurately when given unfamiliar arrangements."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Children need to build familiarity with different arrangements of number. Comment on what you notice eg. 'I can see 3 and 1, I can see 4'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690736Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-one-one-less
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse one more and one less, particularly when finding missing numbers."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the stem sentence ___ is one more / one less than ___ because it comes after / before it in our count."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690741Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-space-numbers-equally-consistently
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils do not space numbers equally or consistently on a number line."@en ;
  curric:correction """Show pupils examples of number lines both horizontal and vertical and draw attention to the gaps between numbers. Talk to children about the equal size 'jumps' between them to support understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690745Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-continue-count-finding-sum
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils continue to count all when finding the sum instead of counting on from 10 or using their developing fluency with partitioning teen numbers into 10 and a bit."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide concrete and pictorial examples where 10 is provided as a group that is hard to separate and count. Continue to emphasise one ten as a group of 10 that does not need to be counted in ones."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690752Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-try-estimate-length-without
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may try to estimate length without aligning their object with the start of the known length (such as a 10 cm strip of paper)."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Each time you make an estimate, model aligning the object you are measuring with the start of the strip of paper. Make links to when we measure with a ruler, knowing we always have to line up the object we are measuring with 0 cm."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690756Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-tallest-shape-largest
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may think that the tallest shape is always the largest."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore lots of different 3D shapes of different proportions. Allow children to handle and rotate the shapes. Use hollow shapes and explore filling them with water or sand to help children see that the largest shape is the one that can hold the most."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690761Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-initially-struggle-read-interpret
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may initially struggle to read and interpret the data on the bar chart / graph."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A ruler can be used to help children line up the top of the bar with the scale. Model this as a strategy to support accurate reading."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690863Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-misunderstanding-difference-partitive-quotative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children misunderstanding the difference between partitive and quotative division when discussing the problems."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although they will result in the correct answers, the calculation itself will not accurately reflect the problem. Ensure children initially describe each problem and represent it visually so that they can see whether they are grouping or sharing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690868Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-counting-select-rows-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Confusion when counting select rows on a one hundred square, e.g. children may not use the end of the number (the ones) to help them count accurately, or may say the row ending in 40 is the 'forties'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Label 'decades' throughout the lesson, and model errors in counting within these so that children get used to hearing when the count doesn't sound right."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-recognise-2d-shape-presented
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not recognise a 2D shape when it is presented in a different orientation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Allow children to handle cut-outs of 2D shapes so they can rotate them and explore how the shapes look in different orientations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690877Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-larger-amounts-children-miscount-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "With larger amounts, children may miscount the number of objects."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to mark where 10 objects end, and use this to count on from, rather than always re-starting at one."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690881Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-subtracting-children-partition-whole-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When subtracting, children may partition the whole and the part, look at the ones digits involved and simply subtract the smaller digit from the larger digit, e.g. solve 75 - 36 as 70 - 30, then 6 - 1"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Consider whether or not the equation involved will require the 10 tens boundary to be crossed before solving, referring specifically to subtracting the ones digit from the whole number, e.g. think 75-6 rather than 5 -6"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-spot-pattern-able-continue
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may spot a pattern and be able to continue it based on noticing numbers simply increasing or decreasing without making the generalisations needed to understand why this happens."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to articulate not only the pattern, but also why it has occurred, at first using practical equipment to prove it, then mentally visualising and manipulating the numbers involved."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691022Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inaccurate-use-language-e-g
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Inaccurate use of language e.g. 'Alex is longer than Sam' instead of 'Alex is taller than Sam'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to verbalise the comparisons they make eg. provide sentence scaffolds and ask them to repeat key sentences as a class."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691026Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-need-get-ruler
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that they need to get a ruler and measure length before they can estimate it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce the language of 'about' to show that estimates do not need to be exact. Use known lengths to support estimating within 10cm, for example, practical objects such as paperclips or buttons which are about 1cm in length."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691031Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-begin-confuse-2d-3d
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children might begin to confuse 2D and 3D. For example, describe a cube as a square."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use geometric construction materials to explore the 2D shapes within 3D shapes. Look for familiar 3D shapes in the environment and discuss."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691035Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-make-link-prior-learning
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children do not always make the link to prior learning automatically, so when new numbers are introduced, they can sometimes revert to inefficient strategies."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is important that the use of efficient strategies that are already known are focused upon when equations with new numbers are introduced so that prior knowledge can be used to support new learning and children can continue to work efficiently."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691119Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-rely-counting-tens-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may rely on counting in tens rather than using known facts to add and subtract multiples of ten."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to look for patterns as they add and subtract multiples of ten. Compare to the single-digit facts they know. Ask 'Is there a known fact that can help you?'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691124Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-whole-parts-add
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """As before, children may confuse the whole and the parts, or add them all up to find the total."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Place objects in each part of the bar model and combine them to make the whole, or starting within the whole, partition them into the parts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691130Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-see-three
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children can find it difficult to see if the three parts are equal, particularly when they are presented in different orientations rather than horizontal and vertical lines."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Allow children to handle practical objects and cut-outs of shapes that have been divided into thirds so they can rotate them and see them in different orientations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691135Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-counting-fives-children-revert-pattern
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When counting in fives, children may revert to the pattern of counting in tens after reciting a decade number."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use practical equipment such as ten frames and base ten number boards to highlight why the next number in our count could not be a decade number. Explore the pattern in the digits and display these in the environment to promote further discussion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691139Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-automatically-count-tens-add
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may automatically count on in tens to add a multiple of ten."@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss efficiency and compare different methods. Use practical equipment to draw attention to the relationship between adding multiples of ten in two-digit numbers and the known facts they already possess."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-number-29-39-etc
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Confusion between the number after 29, 39 etc. so saying 29,20 or twenty-none, twenty -ten."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explicitly look at the numbers that follow a number ending in 9 using stem sentence to support."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691232Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-count-multiples-5s
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may struggle to count in multiples of 5s"@en ;
  curric:correction """Use of concrete resources: 10 frame and 5 p coins can support children to practise skip counting in 5s. Then move onto counting in 5s on a number line."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691236Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-same-type-object
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that the same type of object, for example a pencil, can be used as a unit of measure, even when they are different lengths."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Read the story of Pedro's birthday quest again and discuss why the friends using their own footsteps for measuring led to them getting different results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691241Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mistakes-counting-ones-children-able
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mistakes when counting in ones. Children may not be able to visualise numbers to see which is more/greater than, less than or equal to."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Children should continue to practise counting forwards and backwards from a given number to increase confidence of counting within 100. Use number lines or one hundred squares to help children visualise numbers and support comparison."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-confusing-direction-dependent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children can find it confusing that direction is dependent on which way someone is facing, and so forwards, backwards, left or right will not always appear in the same direction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities for children to experience movement in a straight line from different starting points, e.g. chalking a grid on the floor outside for them to move around in, or describing the movement of a toy car as they drive it along a track."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691544Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-even-numbers-partitioned
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that even numbers can only be partitioned into even parts and odd numbers into odd parts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children have plenty of practical experience of partitioning representations of numbers in different ways and talk about what they notice. Using number shapes and tens frames can help to visualise the patterns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691549Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-secure-principles-counting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may not be secure with the principles of counting."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage any and all opportunities to count small collections of objects considering ways in which to count efficiently. Model counting using one-to-one principles and strategies such as organising collections to support counting all."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691553Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-amount-processing-required-task-increases
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When the amount of processing required for a task increases, children often default to inefficient strategies such as counting in ones if the use of efficient strategies are not yet automatic."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When solving problems, continue to focus upon, and discuss, the most efficient strategies to use to ensure that this thinking becomes automatic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691558Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-two-digit-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may think two-digit numbers can only be partitioned into tens and ones."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use practical equipment to manipulate tens and ones on part-part-whole models to help children to understand the many ways that a number can be partitioned."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-exploring-reduction-children-struggle-see
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """After exploring reduction, children may struggle to see partitioning as subtraction because a part is not taken away from the whole."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make strong links between equations and different subtraction contexts by focusing on what the subtrahend represents in each case."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-able-accurately-represent-story
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may not be able to accurately represent the story as an equation."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure that children are able to say what each number represents in a given equation using the story as a scaffold before asking them to write their own equations to represent ‘First, then, then, now’ stories."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691585Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-saying-number-names-order-missing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Saying number names out of order or missing a number name in the sequence."@en ;
  curric:correction "Repeat the number names in the correct order, emphasising the correction made."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691593Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cant-compare-order-numbers-next
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You can't compare and order numbers that are not next to each other in the counting sequence."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Start with numbers close together in the counting sequence and move on to numbers with a larger gap."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-identify-whole-unit-repeat
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children might not identify the whole unit of repeat."@en ;
  curric:correction "Describe the pattern aloud to hear the part that is repeated."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691603Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-left-hand-side-clock-cause
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The left hand side of the clock can cause pupils problems when reading the clock to the half hour. For example, because half past nine is between nine and ten, pupils might read it as half past ten."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Encourage pupils to focus on the word ‘past’ - which number has it gone past?"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691610Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-missing-number-equation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may think the missing number in an equation always has to be the whole."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to record their thinking, bringing attention to the missing part by underlining it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691798Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-use-one-one-correspondence
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils use one to one correspondence to count all rather than counting on from a group of 10 to identify a teen number."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide concrete and pictorial examples where it is more difficult to count the ones in a group of 10 e.g. a bundle of straws or box of pencils. Encourage pupils to use the phrase 'one ten and ...' to focus attention on counting on from 10"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691805Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-recognise-arrangement-still-same-rotated
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Might not recognise that an arrangement is still the same when it has been rotated."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Allow plenty of opportunities for building, rotating and comparing arrangements of cubes, and to view them from different perspectives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691812Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-taller-container-larger
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may think that a taller container always has a larger capacity."@en ;
  curric:correction """Choose tall narrow containers alongside short, wide containers and compare the capacities in different ways, such as recording a measurement for each capacity as well as pouring from one container into another to see which has the greater capacity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691816Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-mix-words-sound-alike
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children might mix up words that sound alike e.g. cube and cuboid."@en ;
  curric:correction """Allow additional practice for children to name shapes throughout the day, particularly those that are familiar within their environment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691900Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-identify-pattern-block-fill-shape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "May not identify which pattern block will fill the shape of a space."@en ;
  curric:correction """Model filling spaces using trial and error, each time describing why it does / does not fit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-identify-grouping-sharing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may struggle to identify grouping and sharing structures."@en ;
  curric:correction """Model the problem visually, using manipulatives such as cubes, counters and numbers lines. Alongside this, present these problems as division equations, discussing with the pupils what each number means."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-divisor-number-dividing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the 'divisor' (the number we are dividing by) always represents the number of groups."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Avoid generalising the divisor as the 'number of group' for every division problem, explaining that this only works in contexts in which grouping takes place. For sharing problems later in the unit, the divisor is the 'size of each group'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-find-whole
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may find it difficult to find the whole when they are told the size of the half and may try to find half of the half."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use a bar model representation to help children see the structure of double and half. Use gesture, colour and/or circling when discussing what each part of the bar model represents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-teen-decade-numbers-e
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Confusion between teen and decade numbers, e.g. 19 and 90, leading to errors in counting 80, 90, 20"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Regular identification and discussion of common errors with opportunities to correct them within this lesson can be replicated beyond it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-fluent-their-doubling-facts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If pupils are not more fluent in their doubling facts within 5 they may struggle to efficiently double and halve larger numbers."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide examples of doubling facts within 5 using representations such as ten frames to support learners."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691930Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-relate-size-number-added
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children may not relate the size of the number added/subtracted to the number at the end of the story."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to predict how the number at the end of the story will change when the number added/subtracted is increased or decreased."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-incorrectly-identify-odd-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may incorrectly identify the odd number 'before' or 'after' the one given."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide practice in the form of missing number problems where children must identify the odd numbers before or after one given. Do this until fluent. Initially, allow children to use a number line. Remove this scaffold once feeling more confident."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691939Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-objects-moved-rearranged-children-re
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When objects are moved or rearranged, children may re-count them to find 'how many'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Setting this lesson up practically will help reinforce that there is no need to re-count the set of objects - show they have just moved."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691977Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-see-pairs-odd-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may see the pairs in an odd number and think it is an even number."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children are looking for the extra one that makes a number odd. Provide opportunities to group other odd sets e.g. pairs of socks, pairs of hands / feet and realising an odd number always has an 'odd' one."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691981Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-number-equal-exact
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may assume that any number is equal to an exact number of number rods."@en ;
  curric:correction """There is a focus on multiples of numbers, especially multiples of 2, 5 and 10 in the lesson, but there is an example of a division calculation with a remainder in the first cycle to help pupils become familiar with this concept."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691986Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-describe-movements-around-grid
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may describe movements around a grid using left, right, up and down rather than using the language of turn e.g. go forward, turn left."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to act out their directions practically so they can feel themselves turning and see that they are making a turn and not taking sideways steps across the path or grid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691990Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-left-right-turns
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse left and right turns when someone else, whose orientation is different from their own, is making a turn."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to move themselves into the same orientation as the person whose turn they are trying to describe so that they can use their own left and right to help see which directions someone else is turning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691995Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-understand-value-set-coins
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may understand the value of each set of coins but incorrectly use a symbol ( < > = ) in comparing them."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage reading from left to right e.g. ___ is less than / greater than ___. Ensure children have opportunities to place the coins within the symbols to understand the correct orientation of them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-align-end-their-object
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may align the end of their object with the end of the ruler, rather than zero."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use a sticker or coloured pen to highlight the zero on the ruler so that children's attention is drawn to the zero when they are measuring length using a ruler."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692191Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-start-counting-number-given
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may start counting on the number given and not recognise that the number before is one less."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model counting back and highlight the number before alongside the manipulatives. Give opportunities for pupils to remove one from a set."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692196Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-add-whole-one-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may add the whole and one part to find the missing part."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage the use of the stem sentence ___ is the whole, ___ is a part and ___ is a part, to reinforce what the numbers represent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-rely-counting-0-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may rely on counting from 0 rather than seeing the five and a bit structure of the numbers 6 to 10 and may therefore not partition efficiently."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use fingers to expose the 5 and a bit structure. 'Grow' a number by putting up fingers one at a time while counting, 'show it' by putting up the fingers all at once, 'throw it' as you quickly throw the number of fingers forwards."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-initially-think-two-quarters
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may initially think that two quarters is larger than one-half because the numerals in the fraction are larger."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Try to avoid introducing the fractions in numeral form until children are familiar with recognising two-quarters in different representations such as shapes and small sets. Support understanding with stem sentences as modelled in this lesson."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692282Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-see-minute-hand-hour
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may see the minute hand as the hour hand, treating wherever the minute hand is pointing to as o'clock."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson deliberately chooses to present clocks featuring just an hour hand to really focus in on its purpose. O'clock times with the hour hand and minute hand feature later in the unit. Explain to pupils that clocks do not only have an hour hand."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692442Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-see-shape-two-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not see that a shape can have two different names e.g. a square is also a rectangle."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use sorting hoops to sort rectangles and not rectangles. Then use a smaller hoop inside the 'rectangles' hoop to help identify the squares."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692447Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-regarding-number-decade-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Confusion regarding the number before the decade numbers, e.g. saying 30, 39"@en ;
  curric:correction """Explicitly look at the patterns in numbers that precede a decade number and discuss errors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-misinterpret-number-groups-size
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may misinterpret the 'number of groups' and 'the size of each group' when reading multiplication equations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the order of multiplication equations, referring to these as '___ groups of ___: there are ___ groups with ___ in each group'. Reinforce this with visual representations such as counters and bar models."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692455Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-knowing-number-counting-backwards
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Knowing the number before when counting backwards."@en ;
  curric:correction """Giving 2 or 3 numbers to establish a pattern then reducing to 2 and then just the given number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692462Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-consider-size-objects-comparing-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """May consider the size of objects when comparing rather than the numerosity of the group."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure any groups compared throughout the day are very obviously different before comparing more small things with fewer large things."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692467Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-part-whole-add
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse the part and the whole, or add the whole and one part to find the missing part."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage the use of the stem sentence ___ is the whole, ___ is a part and ___ is a part, to reinforce what the numbers represent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692471Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-understand-importance-order-tens
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not understand the importance of the order of the tens and ones digits in indicating the value of each part of a two-digit number."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use place value charts, place value arrows and Gattegno charts to reinforce the value of each digit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692513Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-shape-split-straight
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that when a shape has been split straight through the middle that the parts are equal."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to compare the sizes of each part by lining them up next to each other. With paper shapes, children can cut out the parts and lay them on top of each other to see if the parts are equal or unequal in size."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692550Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-identify-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may find it difficult to identify the 'then' part of the story because it is not found by measuring the length of the object."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to make jumps with their finger on the ruler to demonstrate how many cm are between the 'first' length and the 'now' length."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692558Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-identify-direction-turn
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children can struggle to identify which direction a turn is in when it does not start from a 12 o'clock position on a clock."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Allow plenty of opportunities to explore making clockwise and anticlockwise turns that start from many different positions and not always facing up or at the 12 o'clock position."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692563Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-explain-difference
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may find it difficult to explain the difference between capacity and volume."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Look at examples of different containers containing different amounts of liquid and use these stem sentences to support their learning. 'The volume of liquid in A is _ than the volume of liquid in B.' 'The capacity of A is _ than the capacity of B.'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692570Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-10-clock-unusual-minute-hand
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The 10 on a clock is unusual as when the minute hand is pointing to 10, it is 10 minutes to the next hour. Pupils may overgeneralise, thinking, for example, when it points to 9, it is 9 minutes to."""@en ;
  curric:correction """As with many mathematical ideas, regular exploration and practise outside of the lesson is key to truly understanding them. Take frequent opportunities to count in five-minute intervals on a clock using minutes past and minutes to."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692574Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-number-coins-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse the number of coins with their value, so count in ones, or revert to counting in ones. They may have difficulty counting on to reach a value when some coins are already present."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Present situations where both 10 p and 1 p coins are used to reach the same amount to stress the difference in value. Compare sets of 1 p and 10 p coins with sets of 10 p coins drawing attention to the importance of the value of each coin."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-patterns-identify-combinations-easy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When using patterns to identify combinations, it will be easy to make errors in recording."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Spend time exploring the value of recording combinations within a simple table. Encourage checking, e.g. the amount of counters totals 5."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692638Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-missing-numbers-teens-especially-counting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Missing out numbers in the teens especially when counting backwards."@en ;
  curric:correction "Repeat the count and stress the missing numbers."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-ovals-circles
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may think that ovals are also circles."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that the outside of a circle is always an equal distance from the centre by exploring and drawing around different cut-outs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-believe-equal-sign-placed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may believe the equal sign must always be placed at the end of the equation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities to rearrange equations, initially where both addends are presented as one unit which balances the sum."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692746Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-symbols
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may confuse the symbols < and >"@en ;
  curric:correction """Use lots of practical examples with cubes or objects inside the symbols so children can see the larger end contains the greater amount."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mixing-numerals-eg-6-9
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mixing numerals eg. 6 and 9"@en ;
  curric:correction "Draw attention to each digit and explore their similarities and differences."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692757Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-find-challenging-represent-sharing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may find it challenging to represent sharing problems with a division equation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Continually describe what each number represents in any division equation. Examples on slides 11-13. It's important that pupils do not over generalise this to all division problems (e.g. in grouping problems, the divisor is the size of each group)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-count-sides-vertices-accurately
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children might not count the sides or vertices accurately because they lose track of where they started counting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask children how they can make sure they only count each side or vertex once. Model marking each side or vertex as you count it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-recall-fact-incorrectly-deploying
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may recall a fact incorrectly, deploying the wrong strategy to calculate."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Revisit strategies for calculating within 10 including using knowledge of doubling, near-doubles, odd and even numbers and one more and one less. Spend time practising recall of these facts beyond the lesson."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-focus-ones-digit-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may focus on the ones digit rather than the tens digits. They may calculate inefficiently by counting on/back in ones rather than using the pattern in the tens digits."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use Base 10 equipment alongside one hundred squares to support with understanding the structure of adding or subtracting ten and difference. Encourage children to notice what changes and what stays the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692941Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-revert-inefficient-counting-strategies
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children may revert to inefficient counting strategies involving counting in ones."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide additional practice and display visuals to support around room. Play games to promote fluency little and often as part of daily activities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692946Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-reverse-digits-two-digit
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may reverse the digits in a two-digit number, not understanding the value of each digit, or partition, for example, 54 into 5 and 4"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Return to the use of practical equipment and ask children to prove they are right using it. They could also explain their ideas to a friend to encourage them to spot their own errors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692952Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-finding-previous-multiple-ten-children
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When finding the previous multiple of ten, children may misapply what they know about counting in tens. For example, they may think 30 is before 40, so think 30 is the multiple of ten before 45"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make deliberate errors to discuss and encourage children to visualise, then label, their own number lines marked in tens."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692957Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-partition-addends-addition-involves
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If children partition both addends when addition involves bridging 10, they may forget to add the extra 10 made when combining the ones."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to consider whether an addition will bridge 10 before solving and if so, partition only one addend to reduce the number of steps required, increasing efficiency."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693208Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-partitioned-tens-ones
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that, when partitioned, the tens and ones must be subtracted in the same order as they occur in the two-digit number, e.g. that to subtract 34, you must subtract 30, then 4"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore subtracting tens and ones in any order at this point, looking at the result of this and considering which they find easier."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693217Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-look-numbers-able-visualise
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may look at the numbers but not be able to visualise the context, for example, they may try to undo 6 + 4 = 10 with 10 - 6 = 4"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use practical equipment to illustrate the importance of the number added and subtracted being the same. Link equations to contexts ensuring that children are secure with what each part of an equation represents when linked to a story context."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693222Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-less-fewer-incorrectly-describing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Using less and fewer incorrectly when describing and comparing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce 'fewer' is used for things we can count (not as many) and 'less' is used for things we cannot count (not as much). Explore a range of examples of this together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-slides-recognising-objects-rearranged
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If using slides, not recognising objects have been rearranged and counting all again."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Gather objects to manipulate (either under a visualiser with the whole class, or in front of a small group) so that children can clearly see that none have been added or taken away."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693231Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-number-groups-group
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may confuse the number of groups and group size."@en ;
  curric:correction """Continue to use the number stems and arrays to highlight the relationship between the factors and products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693242Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-incorrectly-identify-even-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may incorrectly identify the even number 'before' or 'after' the one given."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide practice in the form of missing number problems where children must identify the even numbers before or after one given. Do this until fluent. Initially, allow children to use a number line. Remove this scaffold once feeling more confident."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693337Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-part-part-whole-models
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When using part-part-whole models, children may put counters in the parts and whole simultaneously."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Work practically, moving counters to show we can partition the whole into parts and recombine the parts to make the whole again."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693342Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-realise-whole-split-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not realise that a whole can be split in different ways and into more than two parts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide lots of practical partitioning and recombining of objects and record on a part-part-whole model in different orientations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693346Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-errors-counting-things-cannot-seen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Errors in counting things that cannot be seen, touched or moved."@en ;
  curric:correction """Leave only short pauses between sounds to avoid the need for children to hold numbers in their heads. Make actions clear and separate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693351Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-see-four
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children can find it difficult to see if the four parts are equal, particularly when they are presented in different orientations rather than horizontal and vertical lines."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Allow children to handle practical objects and cut-outs of shapes that have been divided into quarters so they can rotate them and see them in different orientations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693358Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-group-ten-worth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that each group of ten is worth more than the last when we count up in tens."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children understand that we count all as we go along to find how many things are in a group, the last number we say tells us how many there are."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693521Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-extend-one-direction-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may only extend in one direction, rather than in all directions beyond a central point."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Count the spaces to fill around the outside, and then count each pattern block as it is placed around the outside."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693525Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-automatically-count-back-tens
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may automatically count back in tens to subtract a multiple of ten."@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss efficiency and compare different methods. Use practical equipment to draw attention to the relationship between adding multiples of ten in two-digit numbers and the known facts they already possess."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-try-count-back-10
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may try to count back from 10 rather than using knowledge of pairs that sum to 10."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use practical equipment to make links between addition and subtraction explicit, demonstrating the relationship on cherry or bar models and number lines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-inequality-symbols-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse the inequality symbols and use them the incorrect way around."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Take time to practise using the symbols with hand signals or using manipulatives. Emphasise the shape of the symbols reflecting their use i.e. more cubes 'fit' into the wider end of the symbol."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693680Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-unable-see-use-learnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may be unable to see how they can use learnt strategies to solve worded problems."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Support children to visualise and represent each problem, first using physical resources that can be manipulated, e.g. socks to make pairs, before looking to represent the mathematics. This will help them to see what they need to calculate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693685Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-align-cubes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children may find it difficult to align the cubes with the ends of the objects, particularly when the object cannot be placed close to the cubes because it is curved or an irregular shape."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use objects such as pencils and pens that can be placed close to the cubes, or support children with aligning the start of the object with the cubes by placing them both against a wall or a straight object such as a book."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693689Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-understand-another
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children can find it difficult to understand that another person's left is not is the same as their own - for example, when facing someone, their partner's left hand is on the opposite side to theirs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model directions from the children's own perspective - face the same way they are facing when you are describing what is on the left and right."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693694Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-miss-numbers-skip-counting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children miss out numbers when skip counting."@en ;
  curric:correction """Children could have resources like number lines to refer to when counting. These can be removed once children become more confident."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693698Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-correctly-read-information
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may struggle to correctly read the information presented within the pictogram/bar chart."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A ruler can be used to help children line up the top of the bar with the scale. Model this as a strategy to support accurate reading."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-bigger-objects-objects
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that bigger objects, or objects that are spread out have a greater value."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that we are counting the number of objects and it does not matter about the size or position."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-get-confused-parts-whole
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may get confused between the parts and the whole."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask the children 'What does this number represent?' and encourage them to use the stem sentences to justify their answers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-connect-known-partition-teen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils do not connect a known partition of a teen number e.g. 16 is 1 ten and 6 ones to a subtraction or addition context and therefore use a less efficient strategy."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Practical experiences using a group of 10 and ones are key to supporting understanding that the partitioning structure can work for different contexts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-missing-object-counting-one-twice
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Missing out an object or counting one twice. Recounting without concluding how many there are."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage using one finger to move and count each object. From the third learning cycle, repeat 'there are ___ [noun]' following a count."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693930Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-size-group-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may be confuse the 'size of group' and  the 'number of groups' in a division equation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Label each part of a division equation e.g. 12 divided into groups of 2 is equal to 6    There are 12 __________ altogether. They have been divided into groups of 2 / there are 2 __________ in each group. There are 6 groups of __________."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693936Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-difficulty-finding-missing-numbers-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Difficulty finding missing numbers when more than one number missing is from a number track."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Encourage and model how to visualise numbers using the numbers that can be seen."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693941Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-start-counting-using-coins
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may start counting out using any coins available instead of thinking of the whole amount needed first and partitioning it into manageable parts where they can deploy known strategies."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to use what they know about making 10, and the numbers up to 10, to find combinations that use the fewest possible coins to total a given value."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693946Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-part-part-whole-model
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When using the part-part-whole model, children may think that the whole is also one of the parts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When using the part-part-whole model, move the objects out of the whole into the parts, and replace the whole with a number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694109Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-ones-terms-extra
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may only think of 'ones' in terms of the extra ones after the tens have been grouped, so may fail to see 45, for example, as 45 ones as well as 4 tens and 5 ones."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When objects are grouped in tens, use deliberate errors and discussion to draw attention to the total number of ones represented by the number, so children are familiar with recognising both the extra ones and the total number of ones in a number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694113Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-see-2-digit-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not see 2-digit numbers as divisible by 10 if they are not in their 10 times tables."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to apply the knowledge that a number is divisible by 10 when it has a ones digit of 0     Examples showing this idea can be explored and displayed to reference within the lesson."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694236Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-struggle-count-multiples-2
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may struggle to count in multiples of 2 and want to count in steps of 1"@en ;
  curric:correction """Use of concrete resources: counters can support children to practise skip counting in 2s"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-mix-hour-hand-minute
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils will often mix the hour hand and the minute hand, labelling each as the other."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson presents two stem sentences which run through each cycle. The use of these stem sentences, alongside frequent opportunities to practise interpreting clocks, outside of the lesson will help pupils to secure the learning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694252Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-able-mentally-calculate-identify
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not be able to mentally calculate or identify efficient strategies and so revert to counting on in ones."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Assess use of mental strategies before starting this lesson as it is important to be fluent in using strategies with smaller numbers before working with larger numbers to avoid reverting to inefficient counting strategies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-addition-subtraction-bar
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse addition and subtraction on bar models and in problems, so may add instead of subtracting or subtract instead of adding."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Cuisenaire rods or strips of paper with numbers written upon them can be manipulated as bar models that represent a problem or equation. This way, the structure of the mathematics can be discussed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694438Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-assume-taller-objects-capacity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may assume that taller objects have more capacity."@en ;
  curric:correction """Compare real containers and demonstrate with water. Taller containers may be thinner and have less capacity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694445Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-able-recognise-five-fingers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not be able to recognise five fingers on a hand or subitise numbers up to five in familiar arrangements such as dice patterns."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Play games to practise subitising and recognising five e.g. dominoes or dice games and finger games such as bunny ears. Allow regular opportunities for pupils to familiarise themselves with common patterns of numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694449Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-standard-non-standard
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse standard and non-standard units, for example measuring the height of a tower by counting the blocks rather than using a ruler to measure its length in centimetres."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use prompts such as, 'How many centimetres tall is this tower?' and, 'The first part of the tower is 10cm tall.' to reinforce the use of centimetres as a standard unit of measure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694461Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-terms-such
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may confuse some of the terms such as 'below' and 'between'."@en ;
  curric:correction """Create visuals to display which will prompt children to think about the meaning of each word. Give opportunities to explore these words in play, for example when building with blocks ask children to place the red block above the green block."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694472Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-name-shape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may find it difficult to name the shape of the faces that cannot be seen in drawings of 3D shapes."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide 3D shapes for children to handle alongside the drawings. Encourage them to visualise the shape rotating to help them identify and describe each face of the shape."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694477Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-particular-facts-children-resort-counting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """With these particular facts, children may resort to counting on in ones from five or six and you want to avoid this."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Begin by linking 5 + 3 in the context of 'five and a bit' to the explicit knowledge that 5 + 3 = 8  With 6 + 3, stress that this can easily be related to 6 + 4 which is a known fact. Encourage pupils to use one hand to represent 5 without counting."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694948Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-size-object-affects
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that the size of an object affects whether it is a whole or not."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show whole objects in different sizes and orientations. Emphasise the language 'whole'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694953Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-continue-counting-tens-reach
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may continue counting in tens when they reach the ones, e.g. count 2 tens and 3 ones completely in tens. They may think arrangement of tens and ones affects how to count them."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make deliberate errors to prompt discussion and refer back to previous stem sentences, e.g. 'The objects are in ones, so I can count them in ones.' Present tens and ones in non-standard arrangements, so children practise always counting tens first."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-failing-match-one-count-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Failing to match one count to one action."@en ;
  curric:correction """Slow the counting and make the action and count very deliberately at the same time so pupils can imitate the modelling."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694964Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-use-cubes-accurately-example
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not use cubes accurately, for example leaving gaps between the objects. They may also miscount the cubes."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to build a straight line of cubes with no gaps first, then place the object they want to measure along the line of cubes. Encourage them to touch each cube as they count."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694969Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-comparative-language-taller
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse the comparative language of taller, tallest, longer and longest."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Talk about the difference between longest and tallest. Collect examples together and label each object as tallest or longest to support children's understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-say-know-name-polygon
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may say that they do not know the name of a polygon when it is an irregular and it does not look familiar to them."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show children a wide range of pentagons and count the sides and vertices of each shape. Agree that these shapes are all pentagons even though they all look different. Repeat with hexagons and octagons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694978Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-shape-larger-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that a shape must be larger because it is wider or longer than another shape, or that the smallest shape should always be the shortest or narrowest."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to focus on the amount of space that a shape takes up. Explore cutting up shapes and manipulating them so that they have the same width or length to help children see which is the largest or smallest shape overall."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694982Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-still-find-difficult-count
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may still find it difficult to count the number of faces, vertices and edges on a 3D shape when they are looking at an image of that shape."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide 3D shapes for the children to handle. Encourage them to mark the faces, vertices and edges with a wipe-clean pen as they count. Talk about where the properties can be found on each shape e.g. a triangular prism has 3 vertices at each end."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694987Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-lots-familiarity-linear-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils will have lots of familiarity with linear number lines but will be less familiar with circular ones. They may not understand that in terms of time, 12 is often followed by 1"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Take frequent opportunities outside of the lesson to practise counting around the clock so that pupils get used to the sequence ... 11, 12, 1, 2 ..."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-try-apply-idea-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children could try to apply this idea to other near-double facts that may be more easily solved using other strategies."""@en ;
  curric:correction """0 + 1 and 1 + 2 are near-doubles, but these are more easily solved using the 'one more'/ 'one less' strategy. Explore this together before leading children to the most efficient strategy for calculating."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695145Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-recognising-subtraction-symbol-children-believe
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """On recognising the subtraction symbol, children may believe that the two parts known must be subtracted from each other, regardless of which part of the equation is missing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use practical equipment on 'First, then, now' boards and on part-part-whole models to demonstrate additive relationships and encourage them to use their number sense to think about and predict plausible answers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695153Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-unable-understand-addends-swapped
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children unable to understand that addends can be swapped but the sum will remain the same."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use a number line to explore commutativity in a situation where it looks less obvious as this will show children the different structures but also different starting pints but the end pint will remain the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695158Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-familiar-counting-ones-find
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may be so familiar with counting in ones that they might find it hard to count in twos."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Try saying all the numbers but whisper or clap the odd numbers to emphasise the even numbers and vice versa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695163Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-linking-one-one-less-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Linking one more or one less than a number to the number after or before in the count."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use objects to model one more being added or one being removed to show one less or fewer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-misconception-multiplying-makes-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may have the misconception that multiplying always makes the number bigger and therefore 0 cannot be a product."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that 0 groups of something is equal to zero. You can show this practically using groups of zero. When a factor is 1 the product is the other factor."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695172Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-name-month-follows
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may struggle to name which month follows December because it is the last month of the year."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The months of the year are presented in both linear and cyclical form. Having the latter displayed in your classroom and using it regularly to recite the months will help them to see that any of the months have a month that comes after them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparing-objects-children-think-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When comparing objects, children may think that one is longer or taller because they have not aligned them to start at the same point."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to place objects on a flat surface such as a table when comparing height, or against a wall when comparing length to make sure that they have the same start point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695444Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-apply-names-2d-shapes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may apply the names of 2D shapes to 3D shapes (such as square and cube)."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Have examples of the confused 2D and 3D shapes (such as square and cube) for the children to handle and explore. Discuss what is the same and what is different about them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695449Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-start-counting-first-coin
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may start counting with the first coin they see or arranged them in a line in no particular order, leading to inefficient counting strategies instead of more efficient calculation methods."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to group coins of the same value together and start with higher value coins, so they can apply the calculation strategies they already know to find the total value of a set of different coins."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-number-odd-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may think a number is an odd number if the tens digit is odd."@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce the tens number being even by showing the groups of 2 We only need to look at the ones digit to see if a number is odd or even."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695540Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-believe-addends-represented-certain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may believe that addends must be represented in a certain order."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure parts are seen alongside objects and pictures presented in different ways so the visual always matches the given expression."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695772Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-terms-minuend-subtrahend-difference-difficult
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The terms minuend, subtrahend and difference may be difficult if only used occasionally."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure the terms are used by the teacher throughout lessons and encourage children to use them when explaining their thinking."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-record-incorrectly-re-add
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If children record incorrectly, they could re-add an addend that has already been used to make a pair to 10"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Carefully model how to record thinking, rewriting the new equation inclusive of 10 underneath."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-use-ten-frames-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children use ten frames but use them to ‘count all’ or ‘count on’ without making 10"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ten frames can provide a great scaffold for all in this lesson when used to 'make 10'. Stress that we partition an addend to make 10 and that once the ten frame is full, it shows one ten so we do not need to count them all."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695924Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-see-link-adding-subtracting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not see the link between adding or subtracting ones and adding or subtracting tens. They may not know how to use known facts to help work out equations using multiples of ten."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce understanding of unitising by describing groups of objects in ones or tens. Make the link between known facts and equations using multiples of ten explicit. Show it with equipment such as base ten blocks and represent on place value charts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695928Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-count-coins-order-already
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may count coins in the order they are already arranged, or begin with smaller value coins first, leading to inefficient counting methods."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Consider the most efficient ways to count, grouping coins of the same value together, starting with greatest value coins or adding groups of coins in ways that enable them to use the addition strategies with which they are already familiar."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-forget-start-whole-group
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may forget to start with the whole group when writing subtraction equations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Maintain a strong focus throughout on what the numbers in equations represent. Explore mistakes that are made to clarify understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696014Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-notice-two-small-two
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children might not notice that the two small and two large triangles are the same size."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Lay the tangram pieces on top of each other to physically explore and compare the size of each piece."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confuse-decade-number-names-teen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "May confuse decade number names with teen numbers e.g. thirteen, thirty."@en ;
  curric:correction """Regular identification and discussion of common errors with opportunities to correct them within this lesson can be replicated beyond it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-incorrectly-partitioning-halving-odd-multiples
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Incorrectly partitioning and halving odd multiples of 10"@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children use representations where they are able to see the partitioning of the number into an even multiple of 10 and 10 more. That way, they can clearly see they are still finding half of 30 for example."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696190Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-forget-move-hour-hand
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes forget to move the hour hand when showing quarter to or quarter past, instead leaving it pointing to the o'clock time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This is covered in Cycle 2 of the lesson. Continual access to a geared clock allows this idea to be revisited both in and beyond the lesson. Plan opportunities for children to see the positions of both hands at quarter past and quarter to."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696194Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-number-groups-total
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse the number of groups with the total, so 3 groups of 5 may be counted as 3 and not 15"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities for children to identify both the number of groups as well as the total throughout. Encourage the use of the stem sentences to support their articulation of this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696199Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-miss-12-reciting-multiples
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children often miss out 12 when reciting the multiples of two due to the irregularity and not hearing the 'two' in twelve."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make deliberate errors around this and use practical objects to show the effect of adding two to ten. Orally rehearse counting in twos, both through and from 10."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696203Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-resort-counting-strategies-find
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may resort to counting strategies to find the difference e.g. counting back four from five to solve 5 - 4"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Always make a clear link between 'all except one' object leaving, and the subtrahend being one less than the minuend."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-finding-missing-ones-digit-addend
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When finding a missing ones digit in an addend, children may confuse the tens and ones digits in the sum, thus adding to the ones to make the amount of the tens digit or vice versa."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Partition the addends into tens and ones so the place value of the digit that is missing is clear."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-describing-partitioning-number-children-mix
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When describing the partitioning of a number, children may mix the parts and the whole."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reinforce the stem sentence, ___ is the whole, ___ is a part and ___ is a part highlighting, the whole and each part using gestures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696793Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-find-difficult-identify-someone
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children can find it difficult to identify someone else's left and right if they are facing a different direction to them."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to orient themselves so they are facing the same way as the person they are identifying the left or right side of. Experience in different ways that when someone is opposite you, their left side is the opposite side to your left."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696797Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-write-addends-order-representing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may write the addends in any order when representing addition as an increase in quantity."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Present and discuss errors, focusing on what each number in an equation represents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-group-objects-counted-tens
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any group of objects can be counted in tens."@en ;
  curric:correction """Identify groups that do and do not have 10 objects, drawing attention to the fact that colour, orientation and size are not relevant."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696927Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-try-make-group-2
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may try to make a group of 2 objects rather than share into 2 equal parts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use the stem sentence 'the whole group of _ has been divided into 2 equal parts and there are _ in each part' alongside concrete objects so that the children can experience dividing different numbers of objects into 2 equal parts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696932Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-understand-why-equal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may struggle to understand why equal groups can / cannot be made."@en ;
  curric:correction """This is a challenging concept for Y2 children without visual representations. Take time to explore how even numbers can be grouped in equal groups of 2, whereas odd numbers cannot be and how multiples of 5 can be grouped into equal groups of five."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696936Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-believe-size-item-relates
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children often believe that the size of the item relates to its mass and that a larger item will always be heavier than a smaller item."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore examples where the larger item is lighter and the smaller item is heavier to address this misconception. For example, compare the mass of an inflated balloon with a stone, or an empty box with a small bag full of coins."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696941Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-week-starts-sunday
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think a week always starts on a Sunday, and a year always starts in January."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Having these displayed in your environment in a circular formation (as in the slide deck) will help to reinforce the idea that a week is any seven days in sequence and a year is any twelve months in sequence. Practise reciting using the cycles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696945Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-e-g-18
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils confuse e.g. 18 and 80 because they sound similar."@en ;
  curric:correction """Take time to emphasise the pronunciation of the teen numbers and provide lots of opportunities for pupils to say and repeat the words. You may wish to practise the teen and decade numbers side by side so pupils can hear the difference."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697127Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-unsure-why-divisor-equal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children are unsure as to why, when the divisor is equal to 1, the quotient is equal to the dividend."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use physical resources e.g. counters or children to represent both sharing and grouping contexts to help children to visualise the idea before applying to abstract equations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697131Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-still-make-errors-selecting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may still make errors when selecting the most appropriate strategy to aid their recall e.g. they may see 7 - 2 = and count back in ones rather than seeing that 5 is the odd number before 7"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Always talk about the equation to solve, modelling thinking processes e.g. 'I can see... so I know.... The table in the first learning cycle, organising facts by the strategies used to recall them, can be displayed within the learning environment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697136Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-mistake-triangle-like-shape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may mistake a 'triangle-like' shape for a triangle."@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide opportunities to explore and handle cut-outs of triangles and triangle-like shapes. Describe and compare how the sides and corners feel. Touch the part of the shape that shows that it is not a triangle and explain how you know."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697140Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-sure-unit-count-confuse
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not be sure which unit to count in. They may confuse the size of the group with the number of groups, for example saying 5 groups of 2 instead of 2 groups of 5."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to draw a ring around each group as they count the groups and display and use the stem sentence to help them describe this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697145Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inaccurate-representation-number-rhymes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Inaccurate representation of the number rhymes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Once again, ensure all children have access to any countable objects needed and ensure the visuals on the slides are not replied upon. Take time to revisit early counting principles, modelling how these can be used to help represent a given visual."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697234Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-higher-level-coloured
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that the higher the level of coloured liquid on a thermometer, the higher the temperature."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore plenty of examples of thermometers with different scales so that children can see that they need to look at the scale in order to compare two temperatures and not just the height of the coloured liquid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-read-scales-accurately-particularly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not read scales accurately, particularly when the type of scale changes from a horizontal line to a circular scale."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Allow plenty of opportunities to explore different types of scales. Find where the same mass would be on different scales and talk about what is the same and what is different about each scale."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697415Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-mistake-triangle-like-shapes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may mistake some 'triangle-like' shapes as triangles."@en ;
  curric:correction """Provide cut-outs of shapes to handle and explore. Make a list of properties a triangle must have and discuss them for each cut-out."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-inaccurately-recall-related-doubling
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may inaccurately recall related doubling facts to solve halving problems."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Represent each problem as a bar model (as the whole and two equal parts) before solving. Encourage children to check that the two equal parts are equal to the whole."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understand-intervals-marks-number
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils do not understand that intervals or marks on a number line need to be equally spaced and that in these cases each mark represents one number."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make connections between number tracks and number lines showing that the intervals are counted on a number line. Expose pupils to vertical and horizontal number lines showing all numbers, including beyond 10, to familiarise them with their structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-find-hard-feel-whether-object
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """May find it hard to feel whether an object is heavier, lighter or equal to the mass of another."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Model using yourself as a scale in different ways - using both hands, picking one object up after another, then having one in each hand."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697445Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-transpose-digits-numbers-add
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may transpose digits in the numbers, so add tens as ones and vice versa. They may also use inefficient counting strategies to count on in tens, then ones."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure that the numbers are partitioned into tens and ones, so their place value is clear and the link to known facts can be easily seen. Refer back to known facts using the stem sentence 'I know that..., so I know that ...'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697449Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-recognise-same-equation-order
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not recognise the same equation when the order of the addends is swapped. They may also think of the equal sign as meaning' the answer is' rather than showing equivalence."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Demonstrate writing equation in different order to that seen in picture or present as mistake to discuss. Refer to equals sign as ‘is equals to’ rather than ‘makes’ or ‘is’ and vary its position in equations to draw attention to its meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697454Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-see-pairs-odd-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may see the pairs in odd numbers and think it is an even number."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children are looking for the extra one that makes a number odd. Provide opportunities to group other odd sets e.g. pairs of socks, pairs of hands / feet and realising an odd number always has an 'odd' one."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697505Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-multiples-5-multiples
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may assume that all multiples of 5 are multiples of 10"@en ;
  curric:correction """Show children the relationship between 5s and 10s using the multiplication chart and number line. Make clear the relationship between the multiples of 5 and 10 through using stem sentences; for every one group of ten, there are two groups of 5"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697657Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-ordinal-cardinal-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Children may confuse ordinal and cardinal numbers."@en ;
  curric:correction """Place an emphasis on these numbers in speech throughout the day. Continue to highlight the links between them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697662Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-use-counting-back-strategies
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may use counting on and back strategies instead of application of known facts and therefore be inefficient when adding and subtracting multiples of 10"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use representations to make clear links when unitising e.g. adding 2 to 3 and then adding 2 groups of 10 to 3 groups of 10, to support children in making the link. Children should be increasingly fluent in addition and subtraction within 10"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697666Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparing-larger-smaller-number-smaller
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When comparing the larger to the smaller number and then the smaller to the larger number, children may record this as 15 - 8 = ? and 8 - 15 = ?"""@en ;
  curric:correction """When finding the difference, we can compare the larger to the smaller number and the smaller to the larger number. Stress that each time, we record this in the same way as subtraction isn't commutative (whole - part = part)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697671Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-difficulty-understanding-partitioning-whole
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may have difficulty understanding partitioning of the whole group where one part is zero."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Include contexts with zero, so children can discuss and clarify their thinking."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697677Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-fluent-number-pairs-partitions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils are not yet fluent in number pairs and partitions of numbers 6 to 10 and so rely on counting to find missing parts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Develop subitising skills so that pupils are able to recognise small partitions instantly. Encourage choral repetition of stem sentences emphasising wholes and parts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-counting-stops-100
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think counting stops at 100 or the regularity of the pattern does not extend past 100"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Count beyond 100 when rote counting, trailing off after 103 or 104 and discussing what would be next to make explicit that numbers do not 'end' at 10. Show numbers past 100 on equipment used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-identify-number-greater-less-another
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """May identify which number is greater than or less than another but then sequence incorrectly."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to visualise each number on a number line so they can see their order. Print a number line for constant use in class."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697725Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-curved-surface-face
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that a curved surface is a face, or the curved line where a curved surface meets a flat face is an edge."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Handle the shapes and discuss how faces and edges feel. Write these descriptions down and use them to help the children distinguish between faces and curved surfaces, or curved lines and edges."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697730Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-understand-importance-order-numerals
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not understand the importance of the order of the numerals in equations, so may not understand that the amount added or subtracted is of key importance when undoing a change made."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Present errors to discuss and correct. Encourage children to use practical equipment to demonstrate how they know they are right or to show why an error made cannot be correct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698041Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-difficulty-sum-presented-left
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may have difficulty when the sum is presented on the left of the equal sign."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure that equations are arranged with the sum both on the left and the right of equal sign. Use term 'is equal to' to stress equality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698197Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-compare-numbers-one-apart-say
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You can compare numbers that are more than one apart and say which numbers are one more or one less."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Make it clear whether pupils are comparing numbers or whether they are giving the values that are one more and one less."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-able-see-doubling-numbers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not be able to see doubling where the numbers cannot be seen e.g. money contexts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Children should be encouraged to represent the numbers using resources to support them in visualising the problem until they are confident to use mental strategies to solve."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698249Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-confuse-left-right-especially
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may confuse left and right, especially when the orientation is different from their own."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage children to change their own orientation to match the turn they are trying to describe. Use arrows to show the direction before and after the turn and ask children to stand and make that turn. Can they feel if they're turning left or right?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698269Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-compare-two-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may struggle to compare two time intervals when they are presented in different formats, such as five minutes to a quarter of an hour."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The lesson encourages converting time into minutes. Develop automaticity in recalling facts such as 15 minutes = quarter of an hour, 30 minutes = half an hour, 45 minutes = three quarters of an hour and 60 minutes = one hour."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698279Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-part-story-change-amount-hard
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "In the ‘then’ part of the story, the change in amount may be hard to identify."@en ;
  curric:correction "Draw attention to the change, talking about it as a increase in amount."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699688Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-change-amount-part-story-hard
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The change in amount during the 'then' part of the story may be hard to identify."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Draw attention to explicitly to the change, talking about it as a decrease."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699730Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-pupils-because-juns-school
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There may be some confusion with pupils because Jun’s school day is likely to be sequenced differently to theirs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Spend some time discussing with the class that daily timetables vary from school to school, and from person to person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700510Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-pupils-because-juns-day
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There may be some confusion with pupils because Jun’s day is likely to be sequenced differently to theirs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Spend some time discussing with the class that people may do things in a different order to each other. For example, some people have a shower or bath in the morning and some have it in the evening."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-misconception-say-monday-first-day
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is not a misconception to say that Monday is the first day of the week. However, generally it is accepted that the first day of the week is Sunday, which is how it will be referred to in this unit."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Discuss with pupils that many people regard Monday as the first day of the week because it is the first day of the working week and that while both Sunday and Monday are acceptable, Sunday is more widely accepted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707634Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-recognise-given-subtraction-calculations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may not recognise given subtraction calculations that involve consecutive numbers and will resort to other strategies to calculate."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Recording equations alongside concrete or pictorial representations (such as cubes or a number line) will help children to visualise the difference and become more confident in spotting equations that contain consecutive numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-name-day-follows
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may struggle to name which day follows Saturday because it is the last day of the week."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In the lesson, the days of the week are presented in both linear and cyclical form. Having the latter displayed in your classroom, and using it regularly to recite the days, will help them to see that any of the days have a day that comes after them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709232Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-assume-answer-questions-posed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children assume that the answer to all questions posed is 0 because that is the focus."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Always encourage children to read an equation aloud and describe the role of each number within it. Relating each to a context can help children to visualise the mathematics when 0 feels abstract."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709525Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
